–Female":"1650–Deceased","1650":"1650","ABT 1675":"about 1675","1670":"1670","1718":"1718","1758":"1758",",,Virginia, United states":"Virginia, United States",", , , England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Virginia, British Colonial America":"Virginia, British Colonial America",", , Virginia, United States":"Virginia, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name for someone from Woodsome (a lost place in Batley), Woodsome in Farnley Tyas, or Wothersome, all in Yorkshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>hūsum</i>, dative plural of <i>hūs</i> ‘house’.","English (Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Ode</i>, <i>Odd(e)</i> + <i>son</i>, with the addition of initial <i>W-</i>, a characteristic dialect feature in the south of Yorkshire."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodsum","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Woodsome</b> (see   Woodson  )."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1671321,"age":108,"year":"1758","julianDay":2363157,"title":"Mount Vernon","description":"Mount Vernon Plantation was the home of George Washington. It started off as 2,000 acres and was later expanded to 8,000 acres. The house itself started off as a six room building then got extended to twenty-one rooms.","url":"https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/presidents/mount_vernon.html","urlTitle":"National Park Service- Mount Vernon","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Jane Woodson was born in 1650, in England, United Kingdom. She married Jacob Sherwood about 1675, in Virginia, United States. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Virginia, United States."},"et":{"1650–":"1650–Surnud","1650–Male":"1650–Surnud","1670–1718":"1670–1718","1650–Female":"1650–Surnud","1650":"1650","ABT 1675":"umbes 1675","1670":"1670","1718":"1718","1758":"1758",",,Virginia, United states":"Virginia, Ameerika Ühendriigid",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Virginia, British Colonial America":"Virginia, British Colonial America",", , Virginia, United States":"Virginia, Ameerika Ühendriigid"},"fi":{"1650–":"1650–Kuollut","1650–Male":"1650–Kuollut","1670–1718":"1670–1718","1650–Female":"1650–Kuollut","1650":"1650","ABT 1675":"noin 1675","1670":"1670","1718":"1718","1758":"1758",",,Virginia, United states":"Virginia, Yhdysvallat",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Virginia, British Colonial America":"Virginia, British Colonial America",", , Virginia, United States":"Virginia, Yhdysvallat"},"fr":{"1650–":"1650–Décédée","1650–Male":"1650–Décédé","1670–1718":"1670–1718","1650–Female":"1650–Décédée","1650":"1650","ABT 1675":"environ 1675","1670":"1670","1718":"171